title: Edmonton public high school attendance by region
name: Edmonton public high school attendance by region
description:
About half of Edmonton public school students go to schools outside their attendance areas. But as more people talk about the value of local schools, The Journal wondered how much of a difference there was in terms of local attendance at schools across the city.

The district provided The Journal with the statistics on how many children reside in each attendance zone and how many attend their local schools. The district also provided the attendance area boundaries. Using that information, we looked at the percentage of local children who attend their local schools. We thought readers would be interested in seeing the details of that analysis.
It should be noted, however, that attendance zones are not always simple to interpret.

Schools that house only programs of choice, such as Edmonton Christian West, Old Scona or the Amiskwaciy Academy, will not appear on this list, because they do not have attendance areas.

Other schools that house multiple grade groupings, such as elementary and junior high students, may have different attendance areas for those different levels. Victoria School, for example, is a K-12 school, but only has an attendance area for high school students. Its arts programming at the elementary and junior high level is considered an alternative program.

There are several schools that share attendance areas with another school, in addition to having zones that are exclusively their own. At the elementary level, those schools are Glenora and Grovenor, Holyrood and Rutherford, Montrose and Mount Royal, Allendale and McKernan, Mount Royal and R. J. Scott. At the junior high level, Allendale and McKernan share an attendance area. Four high schools, including Eastglen and M.E. LaZerte, Lillian Osborne and Strathcona, also have shared attendance zones.

All data current as of Sept. 30, 2010.
